55:01.773 --> 55:03.191
because God
needs another angel.

55:03.316 --> 55:06.152
I think it's just bullshit, and on
some level, I think we all know that.

55:06.235 --> 55:07.529
I mean, don't you?

55:08.738 --> 55:11.157
The angel thing does
seem kind of desperate.

55:11.908 --> 55:13.068
I thought you was a Christian.

55:14.202 --> 55:17.205
I am, but I got some questions.

55:20.166 --> 55:23.252
PIPER: Look, I understand
that religion makes it easier

55:23.378 --> 55:27.047
to deal with all of the random
shitty things that happen to us.

55:28.299 --> 55:32.345
And I wish I could get on that
ride, I'm sure I would be happier.

55:34.806 --> 55:35.891
But I can't.

55:37.183 --> 55:40.896
Feelings aren't enough.
I need it to be real.

55:41.646 --> 55:43.023
I gotta go.

55:43.272 --> 55:45.107
I tried to be your friend.

55:46.150 --> 55:48.444
I hope he makes you very happy.

55:50.279 --> 55:51.573
Excuse me.

55:52.741 --> 55:53.909
(CELL PHONE CHIMING)

55:53.992 --> 55:55.075
Hello?

55:55.201 --> 55:56.703
ANDREW: I'm looking for
Natalie Figueroa.

55:56.786 --> 55:57.913
You found her.

55:58.038 --> 55:59.414
Ms. Figueroa,
this is Andrew Nance

55:59.497 --> 56:01.750
calling from The City Post,
online edition.

56:01.875 --> 56:05.085
I recently caught a public radio
interview with Larry Bloom.

56:05.169 --> 56:08.590
He's engaged to a Litchfield
inmate named Piper Chapman?

56:08.757 --> 56:10.842
I'm sorry, I've never
heard of this person.

56:10.926 --> 56:12.594
Oh. Well in his interview,

56:12.677 --> 56:14.971
Mr. Bloom mentioned some cutbacks
at Litchfield this year.

56:15.095 --> 56:17.974
The closing of the track, for instance,
the GED program shutting down,

56:18.098 --> 56:20.602
medications switched to generics,
those kinds of things.

56:20.727 --> 56:23.448
All of which seem to have been
attributed to budgetary considerations?

56:23.563 --> 56:25.941
Well, we do the best
with what we've got,

56:26.066 --> 56:28.359
but there's always a bottom
line to consider, obviously.

56:28.526 --> 56:30.319
I understand that, obviously.

56:30.445 --> 56:33.281
But, I did some digging into the
budget allocation for New York

56:33.406 --> 56:35.617
and as it turns out, Litchfield
actually got an increase

56:35.700 --> 56:39.161
over the last five
years of $2.3 million.

56:40.622 --> 56:43.750
So, what I'm wondering is,
where did all that money go?

56:46.335 --> 56:48.128
I'll have to look into that.

56:48.337 --> 56:49.737
As I understand it,
you're in charge

56:49.798 --> 56:51.131
of day-to-day
operations at the prison...

56:51.257 --> 56:53.217
I said I'd look into it.

57:06.314 --> 57:08.148
I'm really glad
that you're here.

57:13.321 --> 57:15.531
Listen, neither of us understood
how crazy this was gonna be.

57:15.657 --> 57:17.575
We thought, "Sure,
we'll get married after."

57:17.659 --> 57:19.619
Like, we were just gonna
pick up where we left off.

57:21.830 --> 57:26.250
But, Piper, this, this is
changing you, it's changing me.

57:28.544 --> 57:29.963
You didn't ask for any of this.

57:30.212 --> 57:33.133
No. But we're here.

57:35.343 --> 57:37.470
It's messy and weird

57:38.554 --> 57:42.558
and we're gonna do stupid and
lonely and embarrassing shit.

57:42.684 --> 57:45.854
And either we
can do it together,

57:45.937 --> 57:48.356
get married, now,
in this room, possibly,

57:48.439 --> 57:49.879
as soon as we can
file the paperwork,

57:49.899 --> 57:53.235
and do it as
husband and wife or...

58:00.035 --> 58:01.119
Or we have to break up.

58:01.202 --> 58:03.705
Because this thing that we're
doing now, this in-between?

58:05.498 --> 58:06.541
I can't.

58:09.752 --> 58:10.962
So,

58:14.549 --> 58:16.300
what do you say?

58:21.263 --> 58:23.058
PENNSATUCKY:
You know what I got to do.

58:23.141 --> 58:24.600
Hmm? Hmm?

58:24.726 --> 58:26.186
She disrespected me.

58:26.435 --> 58:28.354
ALL: Mmm-hmm.
Mmm-hmm.

58:28.980 --> 58:30.398
Now,

58:31.440 --> 58:33.735
I'm gonna have to kill her.

